@startuml trust-boundaries
' The eight traffic classes, and which of them cross Kaalm's trust boundary.
' Source of truth: docs/src/security/model.md
!include _style.puml

skinparam wrapWidth 360
skinparam nodesep 20
skinparam ranksep 42
skinparam rectangle {
  roundCorner 4
}

rectangle "**inside the cluster**\nthe network perimeter, not a statement of trust" as TB #line:B71C1C;line.bold;text:B71C1C {

  rectangle "namespace: **kaalm-system**" as nssys #line:1B5E20;line.dashed;text:0b3d0b {
    rectangle "**Kaalm Gateway**" as GW #back:90EE90;line:1B5E20;line.bold;text:0b3d0b
    rectangle "**Kaalm Controller**" as CTRL #back:87CEEB;line:0D47A1;line.bold;text:0a2540
  }

  rectangle "**user namespaces**" as nsuser #line:4A148C;line.dashed;text:2a0a4a {
    rectangle "**Agent** Pod\n**trust tier 4: not trusted**,\neven though it sits inside the perimeter" as AG #back:E6E6FA;line:4A148C;line.bold;text:2a0a4a
  }

  database "**Kubernetes API server**" as API #back:FFD580;line:7a3f00;text:3a1f00
}

rectangle "**outside the cluster**" as OUT #line:8B4513;line.dashed;text:3a1f00 {
  rectangle "**Channel platform**" as PLAT #back:FFE4B5;line:8B4513;line.bold;text:3a1f00
  rectangle "**LLM Provider**" as LLM #back:FFE4B5;line:8B4513;line.bold;text:3a1f00
  rectangle "**callbackUrl receiver**\nchosen by the channel owner.\n**Kaalm does not trust it.**" as CB #back:FFE4B5;line:B71C1C;line.bold;text:3a1f00
}

' ---------- classes that stay inside the boundary ----------
AG -[#1B5E20,bold]-> GW : **1. Agent to LLM Gateway**\nprompts and completions\nin-cluster HTTPS, terminated\nat the gateway

GW -[#1B5E20,bold]-> AG : **4. User Gateway to Agent**\nnormalized message envelope\nPOST /v1/message,\n**bidirectional mTLS**

CTRL -[#4A148C,bold]-> GW : **6. Controller to Gateway**\nactivity timestamps, GET /v1/activity\nmTLS, SAN-based authorization

GW -[#7a3f00]-> API : **7. Gateway to API server**\ntask completion, async payloads,\nbudget partials: all ConfigMaps

CTRL -[#7a3f00]-> API : **8. Controller to and from API server**\nwatches in, CRD updates, Pod creation,\nevents out. Standard apiserver channels.
API -[#7a3f00]-> CTRL

' ---------- inbound across the boundary ----------
PLAT -[#8B4513,bold]-> GW : **3. Channel platform to User Gateway**\ninbound webhook messages\nHTTPS via Ingress\n**inbound: crosses in, never out**

' ---------- the only two edges that leave ----------
GW -[#B71C1C,bold]-> LLM : **2. LLM Gateway to LLM Provider**\nprompts and completions\nHTTPS egress\n**LEAVES THE BOUNDARY**

GW -[#B71C1C,bold]-> CB : **5. User Gateway to callbackUrl**\nasync response and error payloads\nHTTPS, every POST signed (rule 25)\n**LEAVES THE BOUNDARY, and ends at**\n**a receiver Kaalm does not trust**

PLAT -[hidden]down- CB

legend bottom
  **Exactly two of the eight classes leave Kaalm's trust boundary: 2 (provider egress) and 5 (callbackUrl).**
  Both are outbound from the gateway, both are always HTTPS, and both carry prompt or reply content. Class 3
  crosses the boundary inbound. The other five never leave the cluster at all.
  ====
  **Class 5 is the one to reason about hardest.** Its payloads carry agent replies, which may contain PII, and its
  receiver is chosen by the channel owner rather than by Kaalm, so it terminates outside the trust boundary by
  construction. That is why it is signed, allowlist-constrained, and re-resolved before dial with the checked IP
  pinned into the connection: see the SSRF row of the threat model.
  ====
  **Detail the edges above compress.** Class 2 supports custom CA bundles for enterprise environments. Class 5
  is constrained by the deny-internal ranges or gateway.callbackUrl.allowlist, with pre-dial host re-resolution and
  the checked IP pinned into the dial. Class 7 writes per-task completion ConfigMaps into **user namespaces**, and
  async response payloads plus per-replica budget partials into **kaalm-system**.
  ====
  Kaalm does **not** log prompts or completions on any of these classes. This figure is about boundaries only:
  for component responsibilities and the wiring between them, see System Architecture.
endlegend
@enduml
